---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema, medicalWebPageSchema } from '../../../../data/schema.js';

const title = '3–6 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress';
const description = 'A complete guide to 3–6 month milestones including rolling, reaching, laughing, babbling, bearing weight on legs, and sitting with support — based on CDC and AAP milestone checklists.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my 3-month-old to not laugh yet?',
    answer: 'Yes. While some babies let out their first laugh around 3 months, many do not begin laughing until 4 or even 5 months (CDC, 2022). The CDC milestone checklist places laughing as an expected skill by 4 months. If your baby is smiling, making eye contact, and cooing, those are all positive signs.'
  },
  {
    question: 'What should I do if my baby skips rolling and goes straight to sitting?',
    answer: 'Some babies do exactly this, and it is not generally a concern. Rolling and sitting use overlapping but different muscle groups. As long as your baby is gaining new motor skills and showing progress, the exact order can vary. Mention it to your pediatrician so they can confirm overall motor development is on track.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my 5-month-old to not bear weight on their legs?',
    answer: 'Many babies enjoy "standing" on your lap by 5 months, but not all do. Some babies prefer sitting or floor play and show less interest in weight-bearing activities. If your baby has good muscle tone and is meeting other milestones like reaching and rolling, there is usually no cause for concern. Discuss it with your pediatrician if you are worried.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Should my baby be responding to their name by 6 months?',
    answer: 'The CDC includes responding to their own name as a milestone by 6 months, though it may be inconsistent at first (CDC, 2022). Your baby might look up sometimes but not every time. If your baby rarely or never responds to sound, including their name, by 6 months, bring it up with your pediatrician to rule out hearing concerns.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my baby to only use one hand to reach for things?',
    answer: 'At this age, some hand preference during specific activities is common, but babies should be using both hands. True hand dominance does not develop until around 18 months to 2 years. If your baby consistently ignores one hand or one side of the body, let your pediatrician know — it could indicate a need for further evaluation.'
  }
];

const articleData = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/3-6-months/milestones/',
});
const faqData = faqSchema(faqs);
const mSchema = medicalWebPageSchema({
  name: title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/3-6-months/milestones/',
});
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} articleSchema={articleData} faqSchema={faqData} medicalSchema={mSchema} breadcrumbs={[{ label: '3–6 Months', href: '/ages/3-6-months/' }, { label: 'Milestones' }]}>

  <h1>3–6 Month Milestones: What to Expect and Signs of Progress</h1>

  <p class="answer-first">Between 3 and 6 months, most babies learn to roll over in both directions, begin reaching and grasping objects deliberately, produce their first laugh around 3–4 months, and transition from cooing to consonant-vowel babbling like "ba" and "da" (CDC, 2022). This period also brings supported sitting, weight-bearing on legs when held upright, and growing emotional responsiveness including recognizing familiar faces and mirroring expressions.</p>

  <h2>What gross motor milestones should my 3–6 month old reach?</h2>

  <h3>When do babies start rolling over?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">Most babies begin rolling from tummy to back around 4 months, since gravity helps with this direction. Rolling from back to tummy typically follows between 5 and 6 months and requires more core strength and coordination (CDC, 2022). The CDC's milestone checklist identifies rolling over in both directions as an expected skill by 6 months.</p>

  <p>Keep in mind that some babies roll early and often while others take a more cautious approach. Both patterns fall within the range of typical development. Continue offering daily supervised tummy time to build the core and shoulder strength rolling requires.</p>

  <h3>When do babies start reaching and grasping?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">Around 3–4 months, batting at dangling toys transitions into deliberate reaching. By 4–5 months, most babies close their fingers around an object and bring it to their mouth — the palmar grasp (CDC, 2022). By 5–6 months, you will see your baby transferring objects from one hand to the other, a sign that the two brain hemispheres are communicating effectively.</p>

  <p>Offer a variety of safe, differently textured objects to encourage exploration. Everything will go directly into your baby's mouth, which is exactly how they are meant to explore at this age.</p>

  <h3>When do babies start bearing weight on their legs?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">When you hold your baby upright on your lap or on a firm surface, most babies 4–5 months old push down with their feet and "bounce" (CDC, 2022). This weight-bearing practice strengthens the leg muscles and hip joints that will eventually support standing and walking. Not all babies enjoy this activity equally — some love it, while others prefer sitting or lying down. Both responses are typical.</p>

  <h3>When do babies start sitting with support?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">By 5–6 months, most babies can sit in a supported position — propped on their hands in a "tripod" stance or held steady by a caregiver. Independent sitting without any support typically emerges closer to 6–7 months (CDC, 2022). The AAP recommends supervised floor time on a flat surface to help your baby practice this emerging skill.</p>

  <h2>What communication milestones should my 3–6 month old reach?</h2>

  <h3>When do babies start laughing?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">A baby's first real laugh usually appears between 3 and 4 months and is one of the most celebrated milestones of infancy (CDC, 2022). Alongside laughing, you will hear squeals of excitement, raspberry blowing, and growling sounds as your baby experiments with what their voice can do. These playful vocalizations are the foundation of conversational turn-taking.</p>

  <h3>When do babies start babbling?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">The shift from cooing (vowel-only sounds) to babbling (consonant-vowel combinations) is a landmark in speech development. By 4–6 months, most babies produce sounds like "ba," "da," "ga," and "ma" (CDC, 2022). These repetitive syllable strings — "ba-ba-ba" or "da-da-da" — are not words yet, but they represent your baby's growing control over the lips, tongue, and palate.</p>

  <h3>Should my baby be responding to their name by 6 months?</h3>

  <p class="answer-first">By 6 months, many babies will turn or look up when they hear their name, though this skill may be inconsistent at first (CDC, 2022). Name recognition reflects growing auditory discrimination — your baby is learning to pick their name out of the stream of language they hear all day. If your baby rarely or never responds to sound by 6 months, bring it up with your pediatrician.</p>

  <h2>What cognitive and social-emotional milestones should I expect at 3–6 months?</h2>

  <p class="answer-first">Key cognitive milestones between 3 and 6 months include early cause-and-effect learning (kicking a mobile to make it move), recognizing familiar faces, and beginning emotional mirroring — smiling back when you smile (CDC, 2022). These behaviors reflect rapid development in the prefrontal cortex and the limbic system during this period.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Recognizes familiar faces:</strong> By 4–5 months, babies clearly distinguish between familiar caregivers and strangers, often showing preference for known faces.</li>
    <li><strong>Explores cause and effect:</strong> Shaking a rattle to hear the noise, kicking a mobile to make it move — these intentional actions show early problem-solving.</li>
    <li><strong>Shows curiosity:</strong> Babies at this age stare at new objects, track movement across a room, and reach for items that interest them.</li>
    <li><strong>Mirrors emotions:</strong> If you smile, your baby smiles. If you look concerned, they may furrow their brow. This emotional mirroring is an important building block for empathy.</li>
    <li><strong>Enjoys interactive play:</strong> Peek-a-boo, pat-a-cake, and simple songs with hand motions become favorites because they combine social interaction with predictable patterns.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Frequently Asked Questions About 3–6 Month Milestones</h2>

    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3 class="faq-question">{faq.question}</h3>
        <p class="answer-first faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When should I talk to my pediatrician about my baby's milestones?</h2>
    <p>Milestones have a wide range of typical, but some signs suggest your baby may benefit from early evaluation. Talk to your pediatrician if your baby:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not try to reach for or grasp objects by 5 months</li>
      <li>Does not respond to sounds or turn toward your voice</li>
      <li>Does not roll in either direction by 6 months</li>
      <li>Seems very stiff with tight muscles or very floppy</li>
      <li>Does not show affection for caregivers or smile socially by 4 months</li>
      <li>Has difficulty getting objects to their mouth</li>
      <li>Has lost previously acquired skills</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The AAP recommends developmental screening at every well-child visit, with standardized screening tools used at the 9-, 18-, and 30-month visits. Do not wait for a scheduled screening if you have concerns — early intervention services are available in every state and can begin before a formal diagnosis is made.</p>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
